*Write operations — <<<govern: [ transaction ]>>>

  The <<<CreateArticleService>>> declares <<<ArticleRepository>>> as a plain parameter.  The YAML
  file wraps the step in a read/write transaction via <<<govern: [ transaction ]>>>.  If the
  service method throws an exception the transaction is automatically rolled back:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestdatajpa/CreateArticleService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/article.POST.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The <<<@HttpResponse(status = 201)>>> annotation on <<<ObjectResponse>>> changes the default
  HTTP status from <<<200>>> to <<<201 Created>>>.

  The delete service follows the same pattern:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestdatajpa/DeleteArticleService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/article/{id}.DELETE.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Read operations — <<<govern: [ readonly-transaction ]>>>

  Read-only operations use <<<readonly-transaction>>> governance.  The transaction is still
  started (required for lazy-loaded associations) but the database driver may skip undo logging
  and other write-path overhead:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestdatajpa/GetArticleService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/article/{id}.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestdatajpa/ListArticlesService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/article.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}



